    <name>
				<text>14.3.1.4 Find volume of solid of revolution</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>In general, suppose the graph of \(y(x)\) between \(x=a\) and \(x=b\) is rotated about the \(x\)-axis, and the solid so formed is considered to be composed of lots of circular discs of thickness \(\delta x\).</p>

<p>Write down an expression for the radius of a typical disc:</p>
<p>\(\quad r_{\mbox{disc}}=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>

<p>Write down an expression for the volume of a typical disc:</p>
<p>\(\quad V_{\mbox{disc}}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>

<p>The total volume is found by summing these individual volumes and taking the limit as \(\delta x\) tends to zero: \[ \lim_{\delta x\rightarrow 0}\sum_{x=a}^{x=b}\pi y^2\delta x\]</p>
<p>Write down the definite integral which this sum defines:</p>
<table>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>\(\displaystyle \int\)</td>
            <td>
                <table>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>[[input:ans3up]] [[validation:ans3up]]</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>[[input:ans3dn]] [[validation:ans3dn]]</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </td>
            <td> [[input:ans3int]] [[validation:ans3int]] \(\mathrm{d}x\)</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>[[feedback:prt3]]</p><br>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<p>The radious of a typical disc is the \(y\)-coordinate of the function. Hence, \(r_{\mbox{disc}} = {@ta1@}\).</p>
<p>Given the radius and the thickness of the disc, we can compute its volume as \(V_{\mbox{disc}} = {@ta2@}\).</p>
<p>In order to find the total volume bounded by rotating the graph about the \(x\)-axis, we take the limit as \(\delta x\) goes to \(0\) of the sum of the volumes of each disc:
\[
  \lim_{\delta x \to 0} \sum_{x=a}^{x=b} {@ta2@}
  \]</p>
<p>This sum defines the definite integral
\[
  \int_{{@ta3dn@}}^{{@ta3up@}} {{@ta3int@}} \,\mathrm{d}x.
  \]</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
